@NODE Introduction "Introduction"

Introduction

Using a Zip Drive for over 6 months now, I find my self using it on
a weekly basis. I decided to write a utilty that would take care of what
I had to do manually.

This utilty has 2 programs that will :

  - ZipCopy : Copys any Zip Drive in 1 swap if you have 100 meg of temporary
    hard drive space.
  
  - ZipBackup : Backup any hard drive partition of 100 meg or less data
    (Program will not compress the data but leaves full I/O functions).

  - Uses a GUI interface.

I asked a few Amiga programmers to write this utilty but if you want
something done, do it yourself   ;)

@ENDNODE

@NODE Requirements "Requirements"

ZipCopy 1.0 Requirements:

  - IconX in your C directory (you should already have it.)
  - Workbench 2.4 or above.
  - 100 meg of temporary hard drive space on DH0, DH1, HD0 or HD1 for Zipcopy.
  - A Iomega Zip Drive with the device called Zip0:
  - A blank formatted Zip Disk

Recommend formatting Zip disks with FFS, no cache. I find that the Zip disks
don't like the cache and corrupt very easily.


@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation "Installation"

Installation

The program is ready to run. Just copy files where needed.

@ENDNODE

@NODE ZipCopy "ZipCopy"

ZipCopy

ZipCopy will duplicate a Zip drive in 1 swap. Just follow the requestors.

You must have a pre-formmated Zip disk before you begin. I recommend using
FFS with no cache.

It will basically ask you to choose a hard drive partition that has 100
meg of hard drive space free (DH0 or DH1 or HD0 or HD1). 

You will then be asked to insert source/data disk, which is the disk with
data you want to backup up. The device must be called Zip0:. Although the
program is incredibly simple to use, I recommend using 2 test Zip disks
to start.

A directory called zipxyzx will be created on the hard drive partition
you chose. The files are then copied to the hard drive, you will receive
another requestor asking you to insert a blank formatted disk.

The files will be copied to the Zip drive and the zipxyzx directory
on the hard drive will be deleted.



@ENDNODE

@NODE ZipBackup "ZipBackup"

ZipBackup

ZipBackup will backup any hard drive partition of 100 meg or less of data.
The drive will not be compressed which leaves it's full I/O capabilities
(Isn't that what a Zip Drive is for?!!).

ZipBackup will basically ask you to insert a preformatted Zip disk in
the drive (must be device Zip0:) and choose the partition you want backed
up (DH0 or DH1 or HD0 or HD1). The partition must have 100 meg or less of
data.

The ZipBackup Program will then copy all the data from your hard drive
partition to the Zip drive.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Bugs "Bugs"

BUGS AND PROBLEMS

If you are having problems, try a FULL re-format on you Zip disk with
FFS and no cache.

This should not cause problems but do not try viewing the process with
shell or file manager utilities.

No bugs found. Tested on a A1200 with 32 meg ram and DKB 030 50 accelerator.

Please follow the easy instructions of the requestors.

